🔧 Best Practices

✔ Catch specific exceptions
✔ Use finally for cleanup
✔ Create custom exceptions when needed
✔ Avoid using generic except unnecessarily
✔ Log errors in production applications

---

⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ Using bare `except`
❌ Ignoring exceptions
❌ Catching all exceptions blindly
❌ Not providing meaningful error messages
❌ Overusing custom exceptions

---

🧠 Interview Answer (Simple)

> Exception handling in Python is used to manage runtime errors using try, except, else, and finally blocks. Python supports built-in exceptions and also allows developers to create custom exceptions for specific scenarios.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📚 Key Takeaways

✔ Exceptions are runtime errors
✔ `try` contains risky code
✔ `except` handles errors
✔ `else` runs when no error occurs
✔ `finally` always executes
✔ `raise` creates exceptions
✔ Custom exceptions improve application design


